\begin{theorem}
Let $(X, \tau)$ be a separable space. If $\mathcal{F}$ is a point-finite collection of open sets in $X$, then $\mathcal{F}$ is countable.
\end{theorem}
\end{document}

It is known that there are precisely three essentially distinct configurations of nine straight lines, where each line contains exactly three points of intersection. One such configuration is depicted in the figure below. Identify and describe the remaining two configurations.
